post_text:
Update: 11:35 am - All students and staff are safe. We have sent a message to parents of all KISD students on Fort Hood to keep them informed.
------------------------------------------------Original Post:
Meadows Elementary Safety Notice - FALSE ALARM
This morning, the campus administration of Meadows Elementary School received notification of a possible emergency situation on Post, not related to our campus. Out of an abundance of caution, Meadows Elementary School went into lockdown this morning around 10:35 am. Students were also brought into the main building.
Upon further investigation, Fort Hood officials confirmed this was a malfunctioning alarm and there was no emergency situation. We have allowed students to go back to class to resume their learning day.
The safety of our students and staff is our number one priority.

post_text:
UPDATE: KISD Student Struck by Pickup Truck

On Monday, August 31, a KISD middle school student was struck by a pickup truck after exiting the bus near Hilltop Loop and Wales. Killeen ISD worked in coordination with Killeen Police as they conducted the investigation. Through the investigation, the Killeen Police Department cited the former KISD bus driver for failing to activate the warning lights on the bus at the appropriate time.

At this point, our primary concern is the well-being and recovery of the student. Our thoughts and prayers remain with the family. At last check, the student was in stable condition.

All KISD Transportation employees were provided additional training on the proper ways to report emergencies and the importance of all precautionary light and signal protocols.

As student safety is our utmost concern, we remind all drivers to be cautious as students have returned to in-person instruction.

post_text: We are proud to announce our partnership with the Bell County Safe School program. The function of the Bell County Safe School program is to create a one-stop center for all aspects of school safety. The program allows KISD students, staff, parents, and the general public to anonymously provide information. Examples of what can be reported include criminal conduct, bullying, threats of violence, drug use, weapon possession, etc. Anyone may report an anonymous tip 24/7 via phone (254) 526-8477, online (bellcountycrimestoppers.com/programs), or using the P3 Campus App (iOS & Google Play). Qualifying tips may result in a cash reward. #BellCountySafeSchools
text: We are proud to announce our partnership with the Bell County Safe School program. The function of the Bell County Safe School program is to create a one-stop center for all aspects of school safety. The program allows KISD students, staff, parents, and the general public to anonymously provide information. Examples of what can be reported include criminal conduct, bullying, threats of violence, drug use, weapon possession, etc. Anyone may report an anonymous tip 24/7 via phone (254) 526-8477, online (bellcountycrimestoppers.com/programs), or using the P3 Campus App (iOS & Google Play). Qualifying tips may result in a cash reward. #BellCountySafeSchools

Parents, here‚Äôs a few reminders before the day begins:
- Monday is a virtual start ONLY. There will be NO face to face instruction on 8/17.
- This is the first day for EVERYONE! Regardless of whether you chose in-person or remote learning, the first 3 weeks of the school year will be virtual for all students.
- The KISD Technology Hotline is available Monday-Thursday from 7:30 a.m.-8:00 p.m. and Friday from 7:30 a.m.-5:00 p.m.

If you have ANY questions, please refer to the FAQs at www.killeenisd/org/rtl for answers or contact your child‚Äôs school to learn more.

Parents, School starts for all students, virtually on Monday, August 17th. The district has received an overwhelming number of technology and Wi-Fi requests, well-beyond the originally indicated numbers on the survey and intent forms.
The district will not receive additional devices before Monday. Students without access to a device or technology will not be negatively impacted. Killeen ISD is exploring the possibility of opening campuses for face-to-face instruction, before September 8th, for students who do not have access to technology and internet as required by the Texas Education Agency.

‚ñ∂Ô∏è Please click here to read more: https://www.killeenisd.org/first_day_of_school_update

Our Chief Communications and Marketing Officer went live to talk more details, watch here: https://www.facebook.com/killeen.isd/videos/642656193339387/?v=642656193339387

post_text: UPDATE: REOPENING THIS AFTERNOON! The Chaparral Road intersection at the northwest corner of the High School No. 6 reopens this afternoon! Originally scheduled to take 40 days, our team was able to complete the work in 9 days.
shared_text:
Killeen Independent School District
July 12 at 11:00 PM ¬∑

UPDATE: REOPENING THIS AFTERNOON! The Chaparral Road intersection at the northwest corner of the High School No. 6 reopens this afternoon! Originally scheduled to take 40 days, our team was able to complete the work in 9 days.

Original Post 07/13/20: High School No. 6 is currently under construction along Chaparral Road. As part of these expanded facilities Chaparral Road will also be under construction to realign the road with a new intersection into the school. Construction on the intersection begins Monday, July 13, 2020. During this road construction Chaparral Road will closed
between Polmont Rd. and Cedar Ridge Circle. Traffic will be required to detour around this area of construction for up to 45 days while construction is completed. East bound Chaparral traffic from TX-195 will be detoured onto Featherline Rd. Polmont Dr will remain open for access into Yowell Ranch neighborhood. West bound traffic from Stillhouse Lake Rd. shall detour onto E. Trimmier Rd for thru traffic. Chaparral Rd. will be open beyond E Trimmer Rd to Cedar Ridge Cir.

post_text:
It‚Äôs time to #ReturntoLearn
Read more here: www.killeenisd.org/rtl

Killeen ISD has developed two Educational Platforms for the upcoming school year: Traditional In-Person and KISD Virtual Learning. We invite you to visit our website to fully understand the health and safety measures the district is making as we bring students and staff back on our campuses. Additional updates will be provided as they become available. This will include changes to safety and health protocols, enhanced cleaning procedures, and operational and instructional adjustments.

Guidance and requirements from TEA continue to be fluid and our plans will be finalized as we near the start of the school year.

We appreciate your flexibility, support, and understanding as we continue to finalize the details to create a plan to safely #ReturntoLearn in KISD.

Click Here To View: https://www.killeenisd.org/rtl

post_text:
06/25/2020 - Students and Parents, First and foremost, Congratulations to the Class of 2020. Due to the rising number of COVID-19 cases across Texas, and upon further discussion, Killeen ISD has elected to cancel our in-person graduation plan to maintain the health and safety of our graduates, their families, and our staff. Capacity restrictions simply do not provide the ability to use the Bell County Expo Center at this time. We had hoped the delay would have enabled us to hold a more traditional ceremony, however, the current circumstances have not provided this window of opportunity. We understand many of you are awaiting confirmation of our in-person ceremony to make travel arrangements, so we wanted to share this information with you as soon as possible. Our virtual graduations are available to be viewed on our website, www.killeenisd.org/grad1920/. This decision was not made lightly, but we must keep the health and safety of our community at the forefront.
An automated message has been sent to graduates and parents.

Nolan Middle School completed its 59th and final year of operation on Jasper Drive. When the school opened in 1961, it was on an unnamed, unpaved road at the edge of town. Now, Principal Ashley York and her staff prepare to open a new Nolan Middle School, this one in Harker Heights in a fast-developing part of the community to the south.

Read our full story here: https://www.killeenisd.org/nolan_middle_school_past_and_future

Breaking!!! KISD School Board Names New Elementary School!ü•≥ü•≥ü•≥

The Killeen ISD Board of Trustees voted to name the newest Elementary campus currently under construction behind the existing Nolan Middle School during Tuesday‚Äôs board meeting.

The Clifton Park/Bellaire consolidation campus under construction on Jasper road will assume the name of Clifton Park Elementary School. The entrance of the campus will face 2nd street. The 124,760 square foot facility will accommodate 1,050 students and will open in the fall of 2021. The new Clifton Park Elementary School was a part of the 2018 bond and is set to open Fall 2021.

The online application for the Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT) is now open for eligible families.

üö®üö®üö® TO APPLY: Please visit yourtexasbenefits.com/Learn/PEBT

The P-EBT food benefit is for families & students who:

The P-EBT application is open now at: yourtexasbenefits.com/Learn/PEBT

We are Kangaroos. We are Eagles. We are Knights. We are Greywolves. We are Lions. We are Panthers. One team, one vision, one love... We are KISD!

When are the virtual commencement ceremonies occurring? Graduation Dates:
* Early College HS - May 29, 1:00 p.m.
* C.E. Ellison HS - May 30, 3:00 p.m.
* Harker Heights HS - May 30, 8:00 p.m.
* Robert M. Shoemaker HS - May 31, 2:00 p.m.
* Killeen HS - May 31, 7:00 p.m.

How can I watch the virtual graduation ceremonies?
Online: www.killeenisd.org/livetv
On TV: Special thanks to KWTX and the CW12 for agreeing to air all KISD virtual graduations on the CW12, this includes:
+ Spectrum (17, 1212, 20)
+ CW on Grande (812, 12)
+ DirectTV (46, 46.1)
+ Suddenlink

For your convenience, we will also stream live on Facebook.com/killeen.isd

www.killeenisd.org/seniors2020

#WeAreKISD
.
.
.
Special thanks to Mr. James Rawls for helping us edit this video! #ThankYou

Happy Birthday, Tuke Shoemaker! ‚Äì February 27, 2020

It was a party at Shoemaker High School ‚Äì a 95th birthday party for the beloved Tuke Shoemaker, wife of the late retired Gen. Robert M. Shoemaker, namesake of the school. As usual, the school‚Äôs Junior ROTC joined cheerleaders, dance teams, band, choir and leadership groups to make the occasion a festive one. There was even cake and a luncheon.

https://www.killeenisd.org/happy_birthday__tuke_shoemaker_?q=c

Shoemaker S2S Road Trip ‚Äì February 2020

Shoemaker High School‚Äôs active, award-winning Student 2 Student chapter took its expertise on the road, visiting Killeen ISD elementary, middle and high schools and even meeting with student leaders from neighboring Belton High School. The humble student leaders from Shoemaker made clear they were just as interested in learning from their peers as they were in sharing their own strategies to make new students on their campus welcome.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2dk3jEEAxgo&feature=emb_title
---------------------------------------------------------------------
We are Kangaroos. We are Eagles. We are Knights. We are Greywolves. We are Lions. We are Panthers. One team, one vision, one love... We are KISD!

Today kicks off a special series #celebrateKISDseniors Over the course of the next few days, we will celebrate one High School each day. In doing so, we will highlight each school's Valedictorian and Salutatorian as well as, look back at some of our favorite memories from this year! Our hopes is to flood social media with love and support for our incredibly strong and resilient graduating class of 2020! We invite you to comment, share each post,... all in this together, let's go!

#WeAreKISD
#celebrateKISDseniors
#SeniorsSocialSwag

Picking back up our #celebrateKISDseniors, today we celebrate Killeen HS! We'll be taking a look back at some of our favorite memories from this past year.

Starting off with, KHS Choirs performed 51st 'Club Allegro' back on January 2020! For the 51st year, Killeen High School choirs performed their popular Club Allegro show, this year featuring music from the 1980s. Senior Kiara Freeman made the most of her fourth and final appearance in the annual showcase singing backup in as many acts as her director would allow. ‚ÄúI‚Äôm going to miss Club Allegro when this is over,‚Äù she said during rehearsal. ‚ÄúThis is a show that makes everyone welcome and it shows the beautiful talent that KHS has to offer.‚Äù #GoRoos #AllGritNoQuit

Read our full story here:
https://www.killeenisd.org/khs_club_allegro_set_friday?q=c

üèä‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è Remember when Harker Heights High School swimmer Timothy Brooks made it all the way to the #state meet this year? In January, he set a new school standard in his signature race, clocking a 51.69 in the 100-yard fly, a mark he bested less than a month later. At the region meet Feb. 1, the Harker Heights senior swam a 50.3 fly, good for a new school record again, a second-place finish and a spot in the state swim meet at the University of Texas at Austin. He was .09 seconds from first place.

üñ§‚ù§Ô∏è ‚ÄúHe has great humility,‚Äù said swim coach David Rosenbaum. ‚ÄúHe‚Äôs not boastful, even when he has every right to be. He values work ethic over bravado.‚Äù

#GoKnights
Read our full story here:
https://www.killeenisd.org/hhhs_swimmer_going_to_state?q=c
.
.
.

The Harker Heights Knights varsity football team joined their KISD peers in a friendly challenge in the shadow of III Corps Headquarters on Fort Hood, going head to head in several team-building exercises. Even though it wasn‚Äôt about winning, the Knights seemed more than happy to hoist this year‚Äôs first-place trophy. The event, in its fourth year was the idea of Harker Heights High School strength and conditioning coach Garson Skelton and the result of a lot of hard work by Army recruiter Sgt. First Class Leroy Betts.

shared_text:
Killeen Independent School District
May 4 at 11:00 PM ¬∑

A cadre of Killeen ISD high school teachers and administrators began Monday assisting the effort to collect formal senior photos for five virtual high school graduation ceremonies to broadcast later this month. With Career Center photography instructor John Smallwood leading the charge, visual art and photography teachers, along with some recent former KISD graduates are shooting photos, while other educators watch over technology, direct students and parents into five separate entry points in the Career Center parking lot and give soon-to-graduate seniors lots of congratulations.

For more information about getting a formal senior photo completed and other details of graduation, see the following:
https://www.killeenisd.org/seniors2020

post_text:
A cadre of Killeen ISD high school teachers and administrators began Monday assisting the effort to collect formal senior photos for five virtual high school graduation ceremonies to broadcast later this month. With Career Center photography instructor John Smallwood leading the charge, visual art and photography teachers, along with some recent former KISD graduates are shooting photos, while other educators watch over technology, direct students and parents into five separate entry points in the Career Center parking lot and give soon-to-graduate seniors lots of congratulations.

For more information about getting a formal senior photo completed on Tuesday and Wednesday, and other details of graduation, see the following:
https://www.killeenisd.org/seniors2020

Celebrating ECHS! Here's another one of our most favorite memories!
Killeen ISD‚Äôs Early College High School challenges students to a high level of achievement, while providing outlets for fun and games. The first Friday of the school year leading into the three-day Labor Day holiday, the school‚Äôs newest Lions relaxed and enjoyed an annual competition designed to build cohesion and team spirit. New sophomores competed in the morning and the new freshmen competed in the Lion Olympics in the afternoon.

üíõ Early College High School Lion Olympics ‚Äì Aug. 30, 2019
Read our full story here:
https://www.killeenisd.org/echs_lion_olympics?q=c

Hey Lion Class of 2020, remember your first day at ECHS? We do! üòçüëçüëç
üíõ On the first day of school in 2016, Killeen ISD Early College High School began its second year, adding a grade level and relocating from Central Texas College to a repurposed former Smith Middle School building on Fort Hood. Seated in the school gym with a vastly expanded class, Early College sophomore Zauria Dillard said she was excited to meet everyone. ‚ÄúI was really excited,‚Äù she said of arriving at the school. ‚ÄúI was greeting everyone. I had not been here before, but the teachers were helping me out. I‚Äôm ready to be friends with everyone.‚Äù

post_text:
ü§© KISD-TV adds Spanish Bilingual Lessons for Elementary Students!

Killeen ISD is expanding the resources offered to Elementary students with the addition of Bilingual lessons on our Continued Learning Center on KISD-TV Spectrum Channel 17 or online at www.killeenisd.org/livetv.

Families can tune in on Wednesdays, starting tomorrow, at 8:00 a.m. until 3:00 p.m. for pre-kindergarten through fifth-grade lessons in Spanish.

Bilingual teachers have prepared half-hour literacy and math lessons for each grade level that will serve as a resource to mailed packets and the online Continued Learning Center.

The following schedule begins tomorrow and will continue every Wednesday for as long as they are needed.

Lessons will also available on the KISD website, www.killeenisd.org/kisdtvclcvideo.

We miss you and we love you KISD kiddos!

ü•≥ Timber Ridge Assistant Principal earns finalist honor for state award!

For the second time this school year, an assistant principal at Timber Ridge Elementary School is honored for a job well done.

Ron Sursa is one of three finalists for Assistant Principal of the Year for the Association of Professional Educators. The state organization will interview the finalists and announce a winner during its annual conference, scheduled for July.

Earlier in the school year, Sursa‚Äôs counterpart, Timber Ridge Assistant Principal Carmen Hankins received Assistant Principal of the Year honors from the Texas Elementary Principals and Supervisors Association for the Region 12 Education Service Center.

üìí Read our full story here: https://www.killeenisd.org/timber_ridge_assistant_principal_earns_honor

(Fun Fact: Just recently, Mr. Sursa and his wife hosted a virtual field trip here on Facebook and introduced us to the newest baby chicks! Pictured below üê§)

- Breakfast 7:30 a.m. - 8:30 a.m.
- Lunch 11:00 a.m. - 12:30 p.m.

Beginning Tuesday, March 17, free breakfast and free lunch will be served each day to all children ages 0-18. Various locations have been designated as pick-up points regardless of enrollment and economic status. Children must be present in order to pick-up food.

Meals will be available for pick-up at or near the entrance of each campus listed below, children must be present. Please note: The USDA requirement is that children must be present when picking up food.

Robert M. Shoemaker High School (*Meals will be available at the Concession Stand.)
West Ward Elementary
Willow Springs Elementary

+ Nolanville Boys & Girls Club: LUNCH ONLY 11:00 a.m. - 12:30 p.m.

The deadline for submission of an application is Friday, March 27, 2020.

-Harker Heights High School-
‚ÄúIn the Region IV High School Bowling Championship this past Sunday at Killeen Bowlerama, the Harker Heights Knights and Lady Knights both finished 2nd to advance to the Texas State High School Bowling Championship in San Antonio on 28 and 29 March. In the Singles Competition, Jamal Mack averaged 228 to win his division against 17 other boys in Region IV. Additionally, Robert Davie, Jr. (219) finished 2nd, Jayce Borja (199) was 5th, and Shyanne Ciesiolka (177) finished 4th in the girls division. These 4 bowlers will now compete in the #State Singles Championship against 65 of the best high school bowlers in the state of Texas.
üé≥ This is the 15th year in a row our Harker Heights bowlers have gone to STATE! Well done, team!‚Äù
#WeAreKISD

ICYMI: The Union Grove MS Concert Choir and the UGMS Golden Bells dance team performed at the Austin Spurs game last Thursday.
The choir, under the direction of Candace Dunning performed various songs before the game, and the Golden Bells, under the direction of Kelsi Lower performed their outstanding routine during the half-time show.
Both groups gave an outstanding performance and had an unforgettable experience.
Special thanks goes out to all of the Union Grove MS parents and supporters who helped make this trip possible! #GoGrizzlies! üêª

Additionally, on Saturday, February 15 the UGMS Golden Belles participated in the ADTS Heart of Texas Classic contest. They received first place for an officers dance in the middle school category and first place team in the middle school category. They also received fourth place best of the best and were the only middle school to place overall.
.
.
.
#WeAreKISD

post_text:
The Killeen ISD Career Center welcomed 1,081 guests Thursday evening for its College and Career Night. Official numbers showed 360 middle school students and 721 high school students in attendance, many with parents and other family members. Principal Russell Porterfield said the night was an important step to show secondary students and their parents the numerous options at the Career Center and also to give a peek to local opportunities beyond high school. The Career Center offers 34 programs of study in career-focused fields to KISD high school students. More than 20 college and university representatives, as well as military recruiters also provided information.
#WeAreKISD
.
.
.
Killeen ISD College, Career & Military Readiness

post_text:
-Ellison High School-
It's going to be a big day at Vision (EHS Library) on Monday, Feb. 24th! Thanks to a Dollar General Literacy Grant, we will be distributing free copies of the novel in verse, "Long Way Down" to any student who requests one. This is our own "One Book, One School" event, in which students get the book, read it, scan the QR code to comment on the book, and then pass the book along to another student. We will also have poets in the Library from Killeen's own local Poetic Sweet Spot! Also, we will be hosting a Barnes & Noble Book Fair! All Ellison students: Make plans to visit Vision on Monday, Feb. 24th!
#WeAreKISD

Make plans to check out this year‚Äôs Killeen ISD visual art show, beginning with a ribbon-cutting reception at 6 p.m. Monday and continuing all week at the Killeen Civic and Conference Center. The show features a huge variety of elementary, middle school and high school student art representing every imaginable visual art media. The public may view the display throughout the week and is encouraged to attend the culminating community art festival Saturday, Feb. 29 from 10 a.m. to 3 p.m., which includes activities for children.

post_text:
Gateway students participated in a morning of inspiration and motivation.
Chaplain (COL) Khallid Shabazz, Ph.D., and his wife Rhonda Shabazz, MHR were the special guest speakers at the Gateway campus on Tuesday, Feb 18. The couple shared their personal journey of challenges and success reminding students to consider all the consequences of the choices they make and to do their best to make the right one. The sessions ended with hugs and handshakes.

(KISD Community Relations in collaboration with Gateway Middle and High Schools)

#ItTakesAVillage #ThankfulForOurVillage

-Ellison High School-
What a great showing for EHS at this year's Visual Arts Scholastic Event (VASE)! Our Ellison Eagle Art students collected a very impressive 78 gold medals, with 11 students qualifying for the state VASE competition! Congrats to our state qualifiers:

*Koty Caralos
*Christen Conner
*Andre Adkins
*Daejza Alexander
*Phillip Saucedo
*Tyrese Charles
*Cameron Woods
*Adrianna Davis
*Trina Orr

And, two of our Eagles qualified for state TWICE at the same event:

*Geanyah Lopez Laboy
*Julia Rideout

Congrats to these students, and to our awesome Art teachers: Mrs. Caddell, Mr. Esterby, Mrs. Greenway, and Mr. McNiesh. Ellison Eagle Art is soaring!

post_text:
üé≥ ‚ÄúThe Harker Heights Knights moved their record to 9-0 this past Tuesday at Hallmark Lanes by trouncing the Copperas Cove Bulldogs 16-1 to clinch the CENTEX District championship for their 6th district title in-a-row. They were lead by Jayce Borja with games of 261 and 234. Robert Davie, Jr. chipped in for the cause with a 258 game.

In a balanced attack, the Lady Knights overwhelmed a short-handed Lady Dawg squad 17-0 to sew up 2nd place in the district. Shyanne Ciesiolka led all the ladies in scoring. With one match left on the district schedule against the Shoemaker Grey Wolves on 17 February, the Knights bowlers are assured of a spot in the Regional Championships on Sunday, 1 March. Well done; keep it rollin‚Äô.‚Äù

Special thanks to Ms. Nilda Rios - Student Activities Coordinator at Harker Heights High for sharing this update!
#WeAreKISD

post_text: The annual Killeen ISD Safety Week is happening this week, Jan. 27 to 31. Across KISD schools, guest presenters, as well as school nurses and counselors are urging students and staff members to remember to follow safety procedures to stay safe at home and at school and all points in between. Last year, Killeen Police Department patrol and bicycle officers joined Chief Charles Kimble at East Ward Elementary School to discuss safety in the neighborhood. They told students that bicyclists should inspect their bike to make sure tires are firm and reflective gear is visible and should wear helmets and bright clothes. Walkers should stay in groups and report anything suspicious, officers said.

"Over the weekend the chess team competed in the KISD City Championship Tournament at Charles Patterson Middle School. The chess team took FIRST place and are now recognized as the 2019-2020 City Championship Team in the 4th and 5th grade section.We had small but mighty group that represented Skipcha Elementary. All 7 members that competed placed and went home with a trophy or medal. Coach Salazar would like to recognize the following students for their hard work: Daniel and Hayun tied for 11th place, Julian won 8th place, Cameron won 7th place, Carson took 6th place, Will won 5th place, and Carlos placed 2nd. There were 40 students in the section that our chess team competed in. Congratulations Silver Stars."
#WeAreKISD

Killeen ISD Academic Planning Fair: Open to all middle and high school students and parents in Killeen ISD! Come explore options for high school that include:
- Advanced Placement (AP)
- Athletics
- AVID
- Band
- Career & Technical Education
- Choir
- Color Guard
- Dance
- Dual Credit Courses
- Early College High School
- JROTC
- KISD Career Center (16 National Career Clusters)
- Leadership Academy
- Orchestra
- Pathways
- STEM Academy
- Texas Bioscience Institute
And so much more!

Are you already in High School? You are also welcome to join us at the Academic Planning Fair to get help with your Financial Aid (FAFSA) and college applications. Come learn what careers are rapidly growing in our community. Get ready now!

Time: 6:00 pm - 8:00 pm
Location: Killeen Civic and Conference Center
Address: 3601 WS Young Drive, Killeen

For more information, please see your school counselor.

This event is hosted by KISD's College, Career & Military Readiness department.

The Killeen High School Junior ROTC special teams competitors celebrated Wednesday the program‚Äôs third grand championship in four years in the Fort Worth Cowtown Classic Invitational Drill Meet. The largest invitational JROTC drill meet in Texas drew more than 2,000 cadets from 50-plus schools. Fort Worth ISD JROTC leaders delivered the grand champion trophy and numerous individual event medals and trophies to the battalion. School, battalion and visiting leaders praised the cadets for their tradition of working hard and overcoming obstacles.

post_text:
Killeen Student Arrested for Assaulting Teacher

December 10, 2019-- Killeen police arrested a Killeen ISD High School student for assaulting a public servant, a felony offense.

The incident, which was recorded on a cellphone, shows the Killeen ISD employee being assaulted by the student during In-School Suspension.

The district took all appropriate steps both legal and disciplinary in accordance with the law. Our highest priority at Killeen ISD is safety, and behavior like this will never be tolerated.

post_text:
Killeen ISD can confirm a former teacher has been arrested and investigated by police for indecency with a child, outside of KISD. Upon learning of the allegations, the educator was immediately put on leave and the district began an investigation of our own. The individual was a teacher at Harker Heights High School, he was not a coach or involved with athletics for the district.
The charges against the individual does not involve a KISD student nor did any alleged criminal act occur on a KISD campus.
The employee has since been terminated and all information was turned over to police to assist in their investigation.
This case remains under investigation by the U.S. Marshals Office and the district is not able to comment further.

Donations for the annual Food for Families regional drive totaled 45,000 pounds within Killeen ISD schools, more than twice last year‚Äôs figure.

KISD leaders made a concerted effort this year to raise awareness of the 30th annual Food for Families drive, which helps fill shelves at pantries in Killeen and across a nine-county Central Texas region.

Those promotional efforts clearly paid off as 45 KISD schools and four administrative departments conducted individual non-perishable food drives as part of the overall community effort.

post_text:
Killeen Police, in cooperation with Killeen ISD Police, Make Arrest for Threat Against Middle School

November 18, 2019 - Killeen Police arrested a Killeen ISD Middle School student for making a terroristic threat against Nolan Middle School, a felony offense.

Around 7:45 a.m. police received a call alerting them of the threat. Killeen ISD police, in coordination with Killeen Police, quickly worked to secure Nolan Middle school as well as investigate the potential threat. The threat was determined by police to be unfounded.

Within four hours a middle school student was taken into custody and arrested on terroristic threat charges. He was transported to juvenile detention to face prosecution.

The safety of our campus is our highest priority. Our students and staff were never in any danger.

Our students must understand that we are serious about school safety and any students making or spreading false, unverified threats, against our schools will be prosecuted to the fullest extent of the law.

ICYMI: Dallas Cowboys cheerleaders and a team of coaches made up of former NFL players joined Rowdy the mascot on a tour of Killeen ISD schools Friday to promote healthy living and community service. After a visit at Meadows Elementary School, the group of athletes joined Audie Murphy Middle School student leaders at the Clear Creek commissary on Fort Hood where they raced to purchase non-perishable food items for the school‚Äôs food drive. Next, the Cowboys delegation went to the Rosewood Retirement Community to join Rancier Middle School's Youth Congress and some of KISD's AVID students in visiting with residents. Then, the group visited Palo Alto Middle School and planned to finish the day at Liberty Hill Middle School with a sports clinic. Along the way, the Cowboys team donated $500 to Audie Murphy, Rancier and Palo Alto middle schools for their community service efforts. üòÄüëçüëç
#WeAreKISD

Four Dallas Cowboys cheerleaders joined a group of former NFL players and team mascot Rowdy for a Fuel Up to Play 60 mini-camp for Meadows Elementary School fourth-graders Friday. The famous athletes urged students to eat a variety of healthy foods to ‚Äúfuel up‚Äù for 60 minutes a day of activity for an overall healthy lifestyle.
Following the interactive presentation in the cafeteria, the group gathered in the gym for a series of football drills with the coaches and movement exercise with the cheerleaders.

Shoemaker High School sophomore Vanessa Van Dorn returned from the Military Child Education Coalition Frances Hesselbein Student Leadership Program at the U.S. Military Academy at West Point. She attended the elite training with a dozen sophomores and juniors representing six U.S. states and the nation of Germany. Van Dorn shared her experiences Tuesday during the regular meeting of the Shoemaker High Student 2 Student group.
